{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657662"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:32:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:32:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20587"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20587"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.15,0.3,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13464"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93749"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13464"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20587"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76959"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"12504"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12797"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32150"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32155"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93749"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESystemic vasculitides are classified based on the size of affected blood vessels and their pathological features. Small vessel vasculitides can affect capillaries, arterioles, and venules.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about microscopic polyangiitis is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lesions are typically of the same age in affected tissues","Granulomatous inflammation is a hallmark feature","Immune complex deposition is prominent in vessel walls","Medium-sized arteries are primarily affected","Eosinophilic infiltrates are characteristic findings"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELesions are typically of the same age in affected tissues\u003C/strong\u003E in microscopic polyangiitis (MPA), suggesting a single episode of injury. This is in contrast to polyarteritis nodosa (PAN), where lesions of varying ages can be found throughout affected tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatous inflammation is a hallmark feature\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect for MPA. Granulomatous inflammation is characteristic of granulomatosis with polyangiitis (formerly Wegener\u0027s granulomatosis) and eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis (formerly Churg-Strauss syndrome), but MPA lacks granuloma formation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmune complex deposition is prominent in vessel walls\u003C/strong\u003E - MPA is a pauci-immune vasculitis, meaning there are few or no immune deposits in vessel walls. Immune complex deposition is seen in other vasculitides such as IgA vasculitis (Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura).\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedium-sized arteries are primarily affected\u003C/strong\u003E - MPA primarily affects small vessels (capillaries, arterioles, and venules), not medium-sized arteries. Medium vessel involvement is more characteristic of PAN.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEosinophilic infiltrates are characteristic findings\u003C/strong\u003E - Eosinophilic infiltrates are characteristic of eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis, not MPA.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMicroscopic polyangiitis is a pauci-immune small vessel vasculitis associated with anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies (ANCA), particularly those with specificity for myeloperoxidase (MPO-ANCA). The necrotising vasculitis can affect multiple organ systems, with the kidneys and lungs being commonly involved.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Microscopic polyangiitis is a small vessel vasculitis affecting capillaries, arterioles, and venules.","Microscopic polyangiitis is characterised by pauci-immune necrotising inflammation with few or no immune deposits.","Anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies (ANCA) with specificity for myeloperoxidase are commonly found in microscopic polyangiitis."],"references":["Mitchell RN, Halushka MK. Blood vessels. In: Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, editors. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. p. 485\u2013525."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76959"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20587"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76959"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-22T09:48:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-22T09:49:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13464"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93749"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4914"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Blood vessels","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-15T20:38:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-15T20:38:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data